The Australian government strongly opposes Japanese whaling in the Antarctic whale sanctuary, aiming to ban all forms of whaling.
Prime Minister Howard challenges Japan's claim for expanded whale kills, emphasizing the economic value of whale watching.
Despite diplomatic efforts, Japan remains firm on its whaling stance, risking its reputation.
Australia's legal attempts to stop the whaling have faced setbacks, leading to concerns about the future of whale populations.
New Zealand also joins the opposition, exploring legal avenues to prevent Japan from hunting humpback whales.
The International Whaling Commission's ban on commercial whaling faces challenges from pro-whaling nations like Japan and Norway.
